KEYWORDS
Attention-deficit/hyperactiv-
ity disorder; blood–brain
barrier; claudin-5; intestinal
permeability; zonulin
Introduction
Attention-deficit/hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) is one of the most
common neurodevelopmental disorders in childhood and in a
meta-analysis study it has been reported that its prevalence is
5.29% worldwide (Polanczyk and Rohde 2007). In a multicenter
study which was conducted in Turkey, the prevalence of ADHD
was reported to be 12.4% (Ercan et al. 2019). Although the aeti-
ology of this common disorder is still unclear, it is suggested that
multifactorial, genetic, environmental, psychosocial and neurobio-
logical factors play a role in its occurrence (Thapar et al. 2012).
Recently, numerous biomarker research studies have been con-
ducted for determining the aetiology of ADHD (Scassellati et al.
2012). In this context, intestinal and blood–brain barrier (BBB) per-
meability has also been of interest.
The gastrointestinal system (GIS) is the main pathway for the
entry of antigens into the body and the intestines serve as a bar-
rier for the passage of bacteriae. Dysbiosis causes intestinal per-
meability
which
facilitates
many
GIS
and
non-GIS
diseases.
Zonulin is a clinical indicator of intestinal permeability which
weighs 47 kilodaltons and is a signal protein with properties simi-
lar to serine proteases (Fasano et al. 2000). Zonulin serum concen-
tration is closely related to the lactulose/mannitol ratio in urine
which is a marker of intestinal permeability (Sapone et al. 2006).
Two main factors that stimulate the release of zonulin have been
identified: gluten and bacteriae. It has been shown that the
release of zonulin results in bacterial transmission through the
opening of the paracellular pathway by increased intestinal per-
meability and response to the innate immune system (Fasano
2012; Sturgeon and Fasano 2016). The association of zonulin with
coeliac disease, type 1 diabetes mellitus, obesity, irritable bowel
syndrome and ankylosing spondylitis has been investigated and
increased intestinal permeability has been reported to play a role
in the etiopathogenesis of these diseases (Meddings et al. 1999;
Fasano et al. 2000; K€onig et al. 2016; Ciccia et al. 2017). In recent
years, interest in the relationship between increased intestinal
permeability and psychiatric disorders have increased and in this
context, the relationship between various psychiatric disorders
and circulating zonulin levels have been examined (Esnafoglu
