INTERNATIONAL JOURNAL OF PSYCHIATRY IN CLINICAL PRACTICE
https://doi.org/10.1080/13651501.2020.1801754
et al. 2017; €Ozyurt et al. 2018; Barber et al. 2019; Is¸ık et al. 2020;
Kılıc¸ et al. 2020; Usta et al. 2020). In the literature, there is only
one study examining the relationship between ADHD and zonulin
levels. In this study; €Ozyurt et al. (2018) found that children with
ADHD had significantly higher zonulin levels than healthy sub-
jects. The authors suggested that the transmission of dietary anti-
gens or metabolites produced by intestinal bacteriae in ADHD
patients may pass increasingly from the intestine to blood and
blood to the brain due to increased intestinal permeability and
may play a role in the development of the disorder by triggering
possible immune/autoimmune mechanisms and causing neuroin-
flammation (€Ozyurt et al. 2018).
Zonulin regulates both intestinal permeability and BBB perme-
ability (Rahman et al. 2018; Barber et al. 2019). The BBB acts as a
protective gate between the peripheral circulation and the brain,
providing its protective role through the intercellular connections
of the zonula occludens type between capillary endothelial cells.
The transmembrane linker proteins that connect the two mem-
branes are occludins and claudins (Nitta et al. 2003). Claudins are
cell-cell adhesion molecules that are found in tight junctions (TJ)
between epithelial cells. The mammalian claudin family has 27
members and consists of four transmembrane proteins (Tsukita
et al. 2019). Essentially, they participate in the structure of tight
junctions, forming a mechanical connection between individual
cells to prevent the release of solutes and ions from the paracellu-
lar space. Although claudin-5 is primarily localised to the endothe-
lial and epithelial cell layers in the brain, lung, liver, kidney,
intestine and skin it is known to act primarily in the BBB (Rahner
et al. 2001; Daneman et al. 2010). Claudin-5 controls the passage
of molecules smaller than 800 Da in the BBB. Claudin-5 knockout
mice were found to have impaired BBB with increased permeabil-
ity and died within hours after delivery (Nitta et al. 2003).
Although the studies on claudin-5 are limited in the literature, it
has been reported to be associated with epithelial/endothelial
dysfunction and inflammation in various autoimmune, neuro-
logical and psychiatric disorders (G€urol et al. 2015; Y€ucel et al.
2016; Is¸ık et al. 2020; Kılıc¸ et al. 2020; Usta et al. 2020). In one of
the recently published studies, Is¸ık et al. (2020) found serum clau-
din-5 levels higher in patients with obsessive-compulsive disorder
(OCD) than healthy controls (Is¸ık et al. 2020). Fiorentino et al.
(2016) examined the post-mortem cortex and cerebellum of indi-
viduals with autism spectrum disorder (ASD) and healthy controls
revealing that claudin-5 protein and claudin-5 gene expression
levels were significantly higher in the brain parenchyma and cere-
bellum
of
individuals
with
ASD
than
in
healthy
controls
(Fiorentino et al. 2016).
To the best of our knowledge, there remains no study examin-
ing the relationship between ADHD, a neurodevelopmental dis-
order such as ASD and serum claudin-5 level. In this study, it was
planned to examine the serum zonulin and claudin-5 levels of the
children and adolescents with ADHD and healthy controls by con-
trolling the parameters such as age, sex and body mass index
(BMI) percentile which are known to affect these parameters. Also,
we aimed to investigate the relationship between serum levels of
zonulin and claudin-5 and ADHD symptoms and clinical parame-
ters such as depression, anxiety and autistic traits that frequently
accompany ADHD.
Methods
Subjects
This study was conducted between September 2018 and June
2019. Children and adolescents with 8–12 years old ages who
have admitted to the child/adolescent psychiatry outpatient clinic
for the first time and diagnosed with ADHD according to DSM-5
criteria (n ¼ 80) have been recruited and compared with healthy
volunteer controls (n ¼ 40) similar to the patient group in terms
of age and sex. The patients received a diagnosis of ADHD for the
first time and medical treatment was not initiated. Participants
with major psychiatric disorders (such as autism, mental retard-
ation, bipolar and schizophrenia, etc.), chronic diseases (coeliac
disease, Type 1 DM, etc.), active infection, obesity (BMI > 95% per-
centile) and history of corticosteroid or immunomodulatory drugs
use in the last 6 months and had a history of taking psychotropic
medications were excluded from the study. The study was
approved by the Suleyman Demirel University Medical Faculty
Ethics Committee (2018/204). Parents of children and adolescents
who agreed to participate in the study signed a written informed
consent. Verbal assent also was procured from all of the children
and adolescents and their parents.
Diagnostic and symptomatic assessment
Sociodemographic
and
clinical
information
questionnaire
has
been recorded in a form prepared by researchers. Height, weight,
BMI and BMI percentiles of the study groups were measured.
Each patient underwent a detailed diagnostic evaluation by a
child/adolescent psychiatrist (P.A.A.) by using the Schedule for
Affective Disorders and Schizophrenia for School-Aged Children,
Present and Lifetime Version (K-SADS-PL) (Kaufman et al. 1997;
Gokler et al. 2004) and ADHD diagnoses were made according to
the DSM-5 criteria (APA. 2013). Parents and teachers completed
the Turgay DSM IV-Based Child and Adolescent Behavioural
Disorders Screening and Rating Scale (T-DSM-IV-S) (Turgay 1994;
Ercan et al. 2001). Parents also completed the Strengths and
Difficulties Questionnaire (SDQ) (Goodman et al. 2000; G€uvenir
et al. 2008) and Social Responsiveness Scale (SRS) (Constantino
et al. 2003; Unal et al. 2009). Children and adolescents completed
the Revised Child Anxiety and Depression Scales – Child Version
(RCADS-CV) (Ebesutani et al. 2012; Gormez et al. 2017).
Blood samples
Participants’ venous blood specimens were collected between 8
and 10 a.m. after fasting overnight. Blood samples have been cen-
trifuged and the sera have been stored in a deep freezer at
80 C until analysis of each sample. Serum zonulin and claudin-5
levels
were
measured
by
using
commercial
enzyme-linked
immunosorbent assay kits following the protocols of the manufac-
turers (Serum Zonulin ¼ ElabscienceV
R , China; Cat No: E-EL-H5560;
Lot: HA8GQTIPG7; Serum Claudin-5 ¼ USCN Life science, China;
Cat No: SEF295Hu; Lot: L190227335). The results of the analyses
were presented in ng/dl for zonulin and pg/ml for claudin-5.
Intra- and inter-assay coefficients of variation (CV) of zonulin kit
was; intra-assay CV < 10%, inter-assay CV < 10%, claudin-5 kit
was; intra-assay CV < 10%, inter-assay CV < 12%.
Statistics
Our data were analysed on the IBM SPSS 22 Statistics software.
Variables were shown either as a number (n) or as a mean ± stan-
dard deviation (SD). Kolmogorov–Smirnov test was performed to
investigate data distribution and further statistical analysis was
carried out using parametric and non-parametric tests accordingly.
The natural logarithm transformation was used for serum claudin-
5 levels with skewed distribution before the multivariate analysis
2
P. AYDOĞAN AVŞAR ET AL.
of covariance (MANCOVA). The normal distribution of log-claudin-
5 was confirmed by the Kolmogorov–Smirnov test. MANCOVA
was conducted for possible confounding variables. The MANCOVA
analyses was carried out with adjustments for age, sex and BMI
percentile. Effect sizes for MANCOVA for all other group compari-
sons were recorded as partial eta-squared (gp
2; small  0.01, mod-
erate  0.06, large  0.14). For the determination of associations
between clinical and biological variables, correlational analyses
were used in the patient group. Results with p values less than
0.05 (two-tailed) were considered as statistical significance level.
Results
The ADHD group consisted of 80 cases (22 females, 58 males)
and the control group consisted of 40 cases (16 females, 24
males) (v2 ¼ 1.39, p ¼ 0.238). The mean age was 9.7 ± 1.4 years in
the ADHD group and 9.9 ± 1.5 years in the control group (t ¼
0.575, p ¼ 0.567). There was no statistically significant difference
between the two groups in terms of age and sex. The demo-
graphical and clinical features of all subjects are presented in
Tables 1 and 2.
The mean scores of the total and subscale scores of the
RCADS-CV, SDQ, SRS and T-DSM-IV-S were found to be statistically
significantly higher in the ADHD group than the control group
(Table 2). Serum zonulin levels were found 87.8 ± 80.6 ng/ml in
the ADHD group and 88.9 ± 69.2 ng/ml in the control group,
serum claudin-5 levels were found to be 2044.2 ± 1893.5 pg/ml in
the ADHD group and 1382 ± 1404.7 pg/ml in the control group.
When the mean serum zonulin and claudin-5 levels of the two
groups were compared; serum claudin-5 levels were found to be
significantly higher in patients with ADHD (z ¼ 1.99, p ¼ 0.046),
whereas serum zonulin levels were not significantly different
between the two groups (t ¼ 0.076, p ¼ 0.936) (Table 3;
Figure 1).
Since claudin-5 values were positively skewed, logarithmic
transformation was performed. The normal distribution was con-
firmed by the Kolmogorov–Smirnov test. Group comparisons were
made with claudin-5 logarithmic values. Age, sex and BMI per-
centile of the groups were taken as covariant and serum log-clau-
din-5 and zonulin levels were compared with the MANCOVA test.
