Discussion
To the best of our knowledge, this is the first study about serum
levels of zonulin, which is one of the biomarkers of gut perme-
ability and claudin-5, which is one of the components of BBB per-
meability, in patients with ADHD. The prominent finding of the
study was the fact that serum claudin-5 levels were found to be
significantly higher in ADHD patients than in the controls.
However, serum zonulin levels were found to be similar between
the groups.
In the literature, studies about claudin-5 have been reported
to
be
associated
with
epithelial/endothelial
dysfunction
and
inflammation in various autoimmune, neurological and psychiatric
diseases (G€urol et al. 2015; Tamer et al. 2016; Y€ucel et al. 2016;
Is¸ık et al. 2020; Kılıc¸ et al. 2020; Usta et al. 2020). Impairment of
BBB and decrease in endothelial claudin-5 levels have been asso-
ciated with amyotrophic lateral sclerosis, traumatic brain injury,
anxiety behaviour, seizures, migraine, schizophrenia, bipolar dis-
order and OCD (Zhong et al. 2008; Doherty et al. 2016; Fiorentino
et al. 2016; Y€ucel et al. 2016; Menard et al. 2017; Greene et al.
2018). In our study, serum claudin-5 levels were found to be stat-
istically significantly higher in the ADHD group compared to the
healthy control group and it was found that the strength of sig-
nificance increased when BMI percentile, age and sex were con-
trolled. Also, in our study, there was a significant positive
correlation between serum claudin-5 levels and attention deficit
and depression scores in patients with ADHD. Menard et al.
(2017) found a decrease in the expression of claudin-5 and abnor-
mal tight connection structure with impaired continuity in vascu-
lar structures of the nucleus accumbens of the mice in a model of
chronic social stress (Menard et al. 2017). As a result of the
increase in permeability in the BBB, depression-like behaviours
have occurred in mice. They have reported that antidepressant
use prevents claudin-5 loss and increases endurance in the BBB.
They also suggested that the decrease in endothelial claudin-5
expression may cause depressive symptoms by causing BBB
impairment (Menard et al. 2017). Azis et al. (2019) found that elec-
troconvulsive shock treatment increased claudin-5 levels in the
prefrontal cortex and hippocampus in a model of depression and
improved depressive behaviour in rats (Azis et al. 2019). Both
studies given above were animal models investigating claudin-5
at the tissue level (Menard et al. 2017; Azis et al. 2019). In our
study, detection of the relationship between elevated serum clau-
din-5
levels
and
depressive
symptoms
is
reported
first
in
the literature.
Previous studies have shown that there was an abnormal and
disrupted claudin-5 expression in the BBB in schizophrenia and
antipsychotic drugs increase in vitro and in vivo claudin-5 expres-
sion dose-dependently (Greene et al. 2018). In 2019; Maes et al.
reported an increase in IgA response to E-cadherin and claudin-5
paracellular proteins in the serum of schizophrenia patients with
deficit syndrome in their study which indicated an impairment of
BBB and gut-blood barrier (Maes et al. 2019a). Y€ucel et al. (2016)
compared serum claudin-5 levels during the attack periods of
migraine patients with a non-attack period and healthy controls.
Serum claudin-5 levels were found to be significantly higher in
the attack period. It has been reported that claudin-5 elevation
may be an indicator of pain triggering neuroinflammation due to
endothelial dysfunction in the BBB (Y€ucel et al. 2016).
Fiorentino et al. (2016) examined the post-mortem cortex and
cerebellum
of
individuals
with
ASD
and
healthy
controls
(Fiorentino et al. 2016). In these tissues; the levels of brain dam-
age/neuroinflammation markers, matrix metalloprotease-9 (MMP-
9) and translocator protein-18 (TLOP-19) gene expression and
claudin-5 protein and claudin-5 gene expression were found to
be significantly higher in individuals with ASD than healthy con-
trols (Fiorentino et al. 2016). They suggested that this elevation in
serum claudin-5 levels might be an emerging mechanism to com-
pensate for possible impairment in the BBB (Fiorentino et al.
2016). In another study, Is¸ık et al. (2020) detected higher serum
claudin-5 levels in children and adolescents with obsessive-com-
pulsive disorder (OCD) than healthy controls (Is¸ık et al. 2020). The
abovementioned studies have shown that the change of claudin-
5 at the molecular level is very important in determining the
changes in BBB permeability. Based on these previous studies, it
was thought that the significant increase in serum claudin-5 levels
which was demonstrated in our study among ADHD patients may
have emerged as a mechanism of secondary compensation for
increased BBB permeability and may be a marker for neuroinflam-
mation. In the future, immunohistological studies evaluating the
role of claudin-5 in the etiopathogenesis of ADHD may open new
horizons in diagnosis, follow-up and treatment of the disorder.
Figure 1. Box plots representing the distribution of serum zonulin and claudin-5 levels in children and adolescents with ADHD and controls.
4
P. AYDOĞAN AVŞAR ET AL.
Zonulin is used as a biomarker for increased intestinal perme-
ability and leaky gut syndrome (Sturgeon and Fasano 2016; Kim
et al. 2018). High zonulin levels were associated with type-1 DM,
atopic dermatitis, inflammatory bowel disease, irritable bowel syn-
drome and childhood obesity (Watts et al. 2005; Kim et al. 2018;
Sheen et al. 2018; Singh et al. 2019). Since the 1960s, studies
have been conducted to prove the hypothesis that gastrointes-
tinal permeability increased in patients with neurodevelopmental
disorders and mental illnesses. Firstly, researches on the relation-
ship between schizophrenia and coeliac disease were published
in 1961 and 1970 (Graff and Handford 1961; Dohan 1970).
Subsequently; Goodwin et al. (1971) mentioned the brain-intestine
relationship in patients with autism (Goodwin et al. 1971).
Esnafoglu et al. (2017) found that zonulin levels of patients with
ASD were significantly higher than the control group (Esnafoglu
et al. 2017). Kılıc¸ et al. (2020) compared the serum zonulin levels
of 41 patients with bipolar disorder and 41 healthy controls and
found higher serum zonulin levels in patients with bipolar dis-
order (Kılıc¸ et al. 2020). However, in their study, they found that
serum zonulin levels of bipolar disorder cases in manic and remis-
sion did not differ significantly (Kılıc¸ et al. 2020). In addition, Is¸ık
et al. (2020) examined serum zonulin levels in patients with OCD
and found that serum zonulin levels did not differ significantly
between OCD and the healthy control group (Is¸ık et al. 2020).
There is only one study examining serum zonulin levels in
patients with ADHD. In this study, €Ozyurt et al. (2018) compared
serum zonulin levels between 40 children with ADHD and 40
healthy controls. They found that serum zonulin levels were sig-
nificantly higher in the ADHD group (€Ozyurt et al. 2018). In our
study, serum zonulin levels did not differ significantly between
patients with ADHD and the healthy control group. Stevens et al.
(2018) found that plasma levels of zonulin and fatty acid-binding
protein-2 (FABP2) which are intestinal permeability biomarkers
and lipopolysaccharide (LPS) which is a gram (-) bacterial product
were significantly higher in anxiety/depression patients compared
to healthy controls (Stevens et al. 2018). Ohlsson et al. (2019)
found higher levels of FABP2 and significantly lower zonulin levels
in patients with major depressive disorder (MDD) who had
recently attempted suicide when compared with MDD patients
without a history of suicide attempts and healthy controls
(Ohlsson et al. 2019). The authors hypothesised that a high extent
of intestinal epithelial cell death or dysfunction may reduce the
expression of zonulin and lower plasma zonulin levels may be
indicative of greater intestinal permeability (Ohlsson et al. 2019).
In the first of two studies about schizophrenia and zonulin rela-
tionships which were published in 2019; IgM response to zonulin
was found to be significantly higher in patients with schizophre-
nia deficit syndrome than the control group (Maes et al. 2019b).
Contrary to this data; in another study, 98 patients with schizo-
phrenia were evaluated and only 42.9% of the patients had serum
zonulin levels above the cut-off value with no significant correl-
ation between serum zonulin levels and psychiatric symptoms
(Barber et al. 2019).
In various studies investigating the relationship between obes-
ity and zonulin; it was reported that zonulin levels were higher in
obese subjects than to healthy controls and there was a positive
correlation with BMI (K€ume et al. 2017; Kim et al. 2018). Esnafoglu
et al. (2017) also reported a significant positive correlation
between BMI and zonulin levels in the ASD group (Esnafoglu
et al. 2017). Ohlsson et al. (2017) found no correlation between
zonulin levels and GIS diseases but found that zonulin levels were
significantly higher in patients with obesity, increased waist cir-
cumference, high diastolic blood pressure and impaired fasting
glucose (Ohlsson et al. 2017). Obese patients were not included in
our study but in accordance with the literature; serum zonulin lev-
els exhibited a significant positive correlation with BMI. The rea-
son that we did not find a difference in serum zonulin levels
between children with ADHD and healthy controls may be due to
the fact that higher zonulin levels are actually associated with
obesity rather than disease. Ajamian et al. (2019) reported that
despite the increasing popularity of zonulin in detecting intestinal
permeability, commercial zonulin assays which are currently in
use do not detect actual protein as prehaptoglobin-2 and have
methodological inconsistencies (Ajamian et al. 2019). In another
study, it was shown that blood zonulin levels might fluctuate
from undetectable levels in minutes or hours despite excellent
stability of serum zonulin IgA and IgG levels, so it was possible to
obtain reliable results by measuring IgA and IgG antibodies
against tight junction proteins such as zonulin in the assessment
of loss of intestinal barrier integrity (Vojdani et al. 2017). In our
study, serum zonulin levels were determined by ELISA method-
ology and zonulin levels might have been affected by methodo-
logical inconsistencies and fluctuations in serum zonulin levels.
Future studies involving more patients and selecting better con-
trol groups by using monoclonal antibody measurement as a
marker for intestinal permeability may eliminate these inconsist-
ent results about zonulin (Fasano and Hill 2017).
This study had a relatively moderate sample size with 80
patients with ADHD and 40 healthy controls and was not pow-
ered to detect the prognostic significance of serum zonulin and
claudin-5 levels. In addition, lack of subgroups in ADHD cases, an
examination of blood parameters only in serum samples, ignor-
ance of negative early life events and socioeconomic status that
were likely to affect blood parameters and cross-sectional design
of the study were the main limitations of this study.
Conclusion
In conclusion, regardless of the limitations, we found an increase
in serum claudin-5 levels in treatment-naive children and adoles-
cents with ADHD compared with unaffected controls. These find-
ings provide additional evidence for dysregulation of the BBB,
especially abnormalities in claudin-5 function, which may be
involved in the aetiology of ADHD. To corroborate our findings,
future studies with larger groups of a heterogeneous population
addressing the limitations of our study are needed to find out
exactly whether increased claudin-5 levels are the cause or conse-
quence of the disorder process in ADHD or not.
